CodeGauge ‚Äî Automated Code Readiness Scoring (C#/.NET)

## Two Ways to Use CodeGauge

### üñ•Ô∏è Option 1: Command Line (CLI)

For local analysis and CI/CD integration.

```bash
dotnet run --project src/CodeGauge.CLI -- --path C:\MyRepo --verbose
```

### üåê Option 2: Web Interface (NEW!)

For easy browser-based analysis with PDF export.

```bash
dotnet run --project src/CodeGauge.Web/CodeGauge.Web.csproj
# Open http://localhost:5059
```

**Web Features:**
- Paste any public Git repository URL
- Automatic cloning and analysis
- Beautiful results dashboard
- Download professional PDF reports
- No local repo needed

---

## CLI Usage (Detailed)

Overview
- Purpose: Analyze a repository and generate a 0‚Äì100 ‚ÄúCode Readiness Score‚Äù for junior developers, with category breakdown and actionable feedback.
- Stack: C#, .NET 10 Console application.
- Outputs: JSON (machine-readable) and Markdown (human-readable) reports.

What It Does
- Scans .NET/C# repositories for the following categories:
  - Tests & Coverage: Detects tests, attempts to run `dotnet test` with coverage.
  - Code Quality: Estimates cyclomatic complexity, long methods, deep nesting, duplication (heuristics via Roslyn).
  - Commit Hygiene: Uses Git history to assess frequency, message quality, and large commits.
  - Documentation: Checks for README sections and inline comment ratio.
  - Dependency Management: Parses csproj PackageReferences and checks for outdated packages via NuGet API.
  - Error Handling: Detects try/catch usage and basic defensive coding patterns.
  - Lint & Formatting: Attempts `dotnet format --verify-no-changes` and falls back to simple heuristics.
- Produces:
  - JSON report (strict schema per spec)
  - Markdown report (readable, shareable, badge summary)

Installation
- Prerequisites: .NET SDK 10+ installed (verify with `dotnet --version`).
- Build:
  1. Open solution `CodeGauge.sln`.
  2. Run `dotnet restore` then `dotnet build`.

CLI Usage
- Run from repository root or provide `--path`:
  - `dotnet run --project src/CodeGauge.CLI -- --path <repo_path> --out-json <json_path> --out-md <md_path> --verbose`
- Options:
  - `--path`: Target repo path (default: current directory)
  - `--out-json`: JSON output file (default: `codegauge-report.json`)
  - `--out-md`: Markdown output file (default: `codegauge-report.md`)
  - `--verbose`: Extra logs (default: false)

Scoring System (Weights)
- Tests & Coverage: 25
- Code Quality: 25
- Commit Hygiene: 15
- Documentation: 10
- Dependencies: 10
- Error Handling: 10
- Lint & Formatting: 5
- Total: 100

Output Schema (JSON)
{
  "repo_name": "...",
  "primary_language": "C#",
  "total_score": 0,
  "category_scores": {
    "tests": 0,
    "code_quality": 0,
    "commit_hygiene": 0,
    "documentation": 0,
    "dependencies": 0,
    "error_handling": 0,
    "lint_formatting": 0
  },
  "feedback": [
    { "metric": "tests", "score": 0, "issue": "...", "recommendation": "..." }
  ],
  "summary_badge": { "score": 0, "color": "green|yellow|red" }
}

Badge & Tiers
- Color: green (76+), yellow (51‚Äì75), red (0‚Äì50).
- Tier mapping:
  - Junior: 0‚Äì50
  - Mid: 51‚Äì75
  - Senior: 76‚Äì90
  - Elite: 91‚Äì100

Recommendations & Deductions
- Every deduction includes a plain-English explanation and a concrete recommendation.
- Examples:
  - Low coverage: ‚ÄúIncrease test coverage; prioritize critical modules.‚Äù
  - Large commits: ‚ÄúSplit into smaller, reviewable commits.‚Äù
  - Lint failures: ‚ÄúRun `dotnet format` and enforce `.editorconfig`.‚Äù

Trend Analysis (Optional)
- Commit trends over 12 weeks (frequency).
- Coverage trends can be aggregated if reports are stored across runs.
- Complexity trend via aggregated metrics per run.

CI/CD Integration (Optional)
- GitHub Actions example:
  - name: CodeGauge
    on: [push, pull_request]
    jobs:
      analyze:
        runs-on: windows-latest
        steps:
          - uses: actions/checkout@v4
          - uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4
            with:
              dotnet-version: '10.0.x'
          - name: Restore and Build CodeGauge
            run: |
              dotnet restore CodeGauge/CodeGauge/CodeGauge.sln
              dotnet build CodeGauge/CodeGauge/CodeGauge.sln --configuration Release
          - name: Run CodeGauge on repo
            run: |
              dotnet run --project CodeGauge/CodeGauge/src/CodeGauge.CLI -- --path . --out-json codegauge-report.json --out-md codegauge-report.md
          - name: Upload Reports
            uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
            with:
              name: codegauge-reports
              path: |
                codegauge-report.json
                codegauge-report.md

Extensibility
- Modular analyzers via `IAnalyzer` interface; add new language modules under `CodeGauge.<Lang>`.
- Adjust weights via constants in `CodeGauge.Core.Models.Weights`.

Limitations & Notes
- Coverage parsing uses best-effort heuristics for `XPlat Code Coverage` output.
- Dependency updates rely on reachable NuGet API; network failures are tolerated.
- Lint detection prefers `dotnet format` when a solution is present.

Support
- Main language: C#, .NET
- Open issues or extend analyzers under `src/CodeGauge.*`.
